{
  "text": "It has been hypothesized that GITRL is able to activate an intracellular signal following GITR binding [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . This possibility is further suggested by the high homology in the cytoplasmic domain among mouse, human and other mammals (including Bos taurus, Canis familaris, Macaca mulatta and Pan troglodytes), so it is possible to find a conserved defined motif: (E-x-M-P-L-x(2)-Sx(2)-Q-x-A-x-R-x(2)-K-x-W-L). This motif is peculiar to GITRL gene. There is no evidence of domains for kinase or other enzymatic activities and there is no experimental data regarding binding of transduction proteins. The only evidence for a potential transductional role of GITRL is the presence of a potential phosphorilation site on Ser10. ",
  "correct_citation": {
